This is my summary of the 2026 annual meeting of the International Society for Stem Cell Research (ISSCR) in Montreal, CAN.
# 1	Hot topics
These topics permeated many talks and sessions throughout the meeting.
- HiPSC-derived neuron transplants reach the clinic.
- Transcription factor transfection for direct transdifferentiation is becoming more systematic: Clinical trial data on the horizon. 
- Vascularized organoid models, e.g., of the brain, heart, and for tumor infiltration studies become more advanced and more available. 
- The topic of diversity, regarding donor ethnicity, age, and sex, seems to shift from a *nice to have* to a *must have* in the field. Particular emphasis on sex-specific differences of cell behavior. 
- Tissue and organ self-organization during embryonic development.
# 2	Take aways
A list of individual studies that I found particularly interesting or inspiring.
- Three back-to-back phase 1/2a clinical trials from the US, Japan, Sweden and the UK, transferring dopaminergic neuron progenitors derived from either autologous, any allogeneic, or HLA-matched allogeneic hiPSC. Scripps, CiRA, and U Lund with U Cambridge. Other talks also presented data for the transfer of iPSC-derived neurons to treat Huntington's disease, epilepsy, stroke, and spinal cord injury. 
	- Studies ongoing. One year results suggest safety but limited effectiveness. 
	- Abysmal cell survival rates despite immune suppression was a central issue.
	>Comment Willem Buys: My lab works with MoroPlur TIRN stem cells (ISSCR 2026 Poster W1228; manuscript in preparation), which were developed at the Zambidis lab, and may offer a solution to these issues. TIRN stem cells have less lineage bias of differentiation, which may provide a real benefit for autologous or haplo-bank settings. TIRN stem cell-derived cell products have repeatedly demonstrated reduced apoptosis, improved proliferation, and improved persistence ([1](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24163065/), [2](https://iovs.arvojournals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2781464)), compared to isogenic primed pluripotent stem cell progeny. 
- Immune stealth iPSC beyond CIITA and b2m KO:
	- Andras Nagy, Mt. Sinai, generated mutant cells overexpressing various macrophage, NK, T-cell checkpoint ligands, induced apoptosis inhibitors, and dendritic cell migration inhibitors. Cells are not being rejected after xenograft transplants even though their HLA-system is intact. [Example Publication](https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.stemcr.2026.102850). 
	- Shin’ya Yamanaka, CiRA: A third way of producing _immune stealth_ iPSC-products. Instead of knocking out all HLA-molecules by CIITA and b2m KO, only knock-out HLA class 2, HLA A and HLA B. By selecting HLA C homozygous donors, matching becomes trivial (a haplobank of this kind only needs to capture HLA-C variance in the population), but cells retain some protection from NK-cells, as well as protecting the host from iPSC-products serving as virus reservoir or an 'immune invisible' malignant tumor.
- Gene editing and therapy:
	- Katie Galloway, MIT: Neighboring genes at least up to 2kB distance repress each other when placed in a convergent orientation and enhance each other when placed in a divergent orientation due to supercoiling. Highly relevant for transgene construction. [Example Publication](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.adw1925). 
	- Feng Zhang, MIT: Human genomes encode many ancient retroviruses that entered the germ line during our evolution. One such gene, dARC, spontaneously forms nanoparticles in the presence of nucleic acids. dARC natively targets muscle cells. Due to its fully human nature, it is much less immunogenic than conventional viral gene therapy vectors.
	- Ho Cheol Cho, JHU presents a single intracardiac injection mRNA-based, non-integrating, permanent transdifferentiaton of ventricular cardiomyocytes to pacemaker cardiomyocytes. While initially focusing on sick-sinus-syndrome, this may rival the billion dollar electronic pacemaker market.
- Hematopoietic Stem Cell Potency:
	- Guy Sauvageau, U Montreal: UM171, a small molecule drug keeping HSPC 'stemmy' during expansion reaches conditional approval in Europe after multiple impressive phase 2 trials of expanded cord blood HSC transplantation. A follow-up substance, UM6XX, is orally bioavailable, kills AML blasts and expands bHSC in a mouse model of AML within 7 days. 
	- Shalin H Naik, WEHI, proposes the multi-track model of human hematopoiesis. Based on HSC-culture splitting and elegant tracing of individual clones, Dr. Naik proposes that individual HSC are already _locked in_ to produce one particular effector lineage with very limited plasticity to produce other hematopoietic progeny. [Example publication](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S000649712600916X). 
- Immune cell therapies: Natalie Shiff, Fate therapeutics: FT819-102, iPSC derived TCR<sub>null</sub> allo 2nd gen anti-CD19 CAR-T therapy against 2nd line therapy failure rheumatic sclerotic diseases. Reduced T-cell depletion regimen enables outpatient therapy.
- Embryonic development: 
	- Bianca Dumitrascu, Columbia University, presents WaxMorph AI, modeling organ development in silico through the interaction of the individual cells and growth factor gradients produced by discrete organizing centers. [Example Publication](https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.64898/2026.07.02.736195v2). 
	- ...Dr Sharad Ramanathan, Harvard, models the effects of such embryonic organizers in vitro in a high-throughput manner.
	- ...Alain Chédotal, Institut de la Vision, screens intact primary embryos in a high-throughput manner at 2.3µm resolution by using tissue-clearing, light-sheet microscopy, and manual annotation, confirming these same self-organizing developmental systems in real embryo development over time. 
# 3	Techniques
A list of fascinating techniques and materials I learned about at this year's ISSCR conference. I have no conflict of interests for any of these technologies.
- Qureator injection-molded (instead of handcrafted or 3D printed) microfluidics chips promise to make vascularized organoids and single-organoid culture much more affordable. Including a "Patho-Chip" optimized for organoid sectioning. 
- Craig Lab, McGill University: Classic deterministic mathematical models (no neural nets or other AI) can capture bone marrow developmental processes to a useful degree, enabling in silico studies after fine-tuning parameters.
- IonQ, MD, has demonstrated proof-of-concept for off-loading some complex combinatorics tasks, like predicting molecular conformations or reaction conditions, to their quantum computer, drastically speeding up computation compared to a pure Turing-machine in silico calculation.
- Tsukahara, CiRA: Sendai-virus hiPSC reprogramming in a closed system using the CliniMACS prodigy. This enables GMP-manufacturing without requiring a clean-room.
